column2: Give each requirement a unique ID.
column3: The feature, function, condition or capability that is required from the project, product, service or result.
column4: The stakeholder who requested the requirement.
column5: The category or grouping of the requirement for example: functional, technical, operational, KPI (result metric), transitional.
column6: The priority of the requirement for example: P1, P2, P3 or MoSCoW (Must have, should have, could have, won't have).
column7: The criteria that the requirement must have for it to be accepted by the project stakeholders.
column8: An indication of how complex it will be to deliver the requirement. For example, High, Medium, Low or Very Simple, Simple, hard, not possible, not possible now�
column9: Whether the requirement is going to be in the scope of the project. This will be agreed by the project sponsor/project board following requirements analysis.
column10: How the requirement will be checked and tested. For example, passes building regulations check.
column11: The project phase or product release number when the requirement will be delivered.
